e voter data and strategies that were so obviously wrong, they shut off the=
ir Twitter account and are patting each other on the back,=E2=80=9D said a =
former D.N.C. consultant, taking a swipe at top Harris advisor David Plouff=
e, who deleted his social media profile after posting, =E2=80=9CWe dug out =
of a deep hole but not enough.=E2=80=9D

The perceived mismanagement of the Democrats=E2=80=99 financial juggernaut =
has instigated plenty of finger-pointing, too. =E2=80=9CWe spent money in s=
tupid ways because we had a really bad strategy,=E2=80=9D said the former o=
fficial, pointing to the
money the D.N.C. lavished on Colin Allred=E2=80=99s long-shot Senate race i=
n Texas, which he lost by nearly nine points, and the late decision to move=
 money into Iowa, another state that the party hasn=E2=80=99t won since 201=
2.

Obviously, Harris is hardly the first presidential candidate to go into deb=
t. Hillary Clinton ended her 2008 campaign owing about $25 million. What=E2=
=80=99s riling up some D.N.C. insiders now is the allegation that they were=
 left largely in the dark about the 2024 budget. The numbers were closely g=
uarded by Biden campaign manager Jen O=E2=80=99Malley Dillon, who stayed on=
 with Harris. I=E2=80=99m told even Harris didn=E2=80=99t know she was in d=
ebt, which certainly makes sense in the final weeks of a down-to-the-wire, =
high anxiety race. (Perhaps better to run into debt and win, the thinking g=
oes, than lose because you=E2=80=99re being too frugal.) =E2=80=9CThey neve=
r shared the budget when they were asked,=E2=80=9D a source familiar with t=
he finances said. A
D.N.C. official said that the majority of money spent was on major events, =
paid media, and the campaign=E2=80=99s much-discussed, supposedly formidabl=
e ground game.

Of course, there=E2=80=99s still plenty of blame to go around. Other Democr=
ats are funneling their ire toward Future Forward, the Democratic super PAC=
 that raised a staggering $700 million in combination with its nonprofit gr=
oup. In the campaign=E2=80=99s closing weeks, the group funded a massive di=
gital advertising campaign that may have contributed to the sense of moment=
um Harris enjoyed in the final sprint, but which was clearly not effective =
enough. In any case, said a D.N.C. member, =E2=80=9CI hope this is the end =
of the people who keep losing every campaign.=E2=80=9D

