16px; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Yes, we=E2=80=99=
re in the still-warm ashes of the 2024 election, but party strategists are =
<i>already</i> plotting and fretting about 2026. Republicans are on an incr=
edible high after capturing the presidency, the Senate, and likely the Hous=
e, but they know the midterms will be stacked against them. An unshackled T=
rump will almost certainly reignite enthusiasm on the left, and historicall=
y speaking, Republican candidates don=E2=80=99t fare as well when he=E2=80=
=99s <i>not </i>on the ballot. The 2018 Democratic landslide remains a fres=
h memory.  <br/><br/>Democrats may be apoplectic and livid with one another=
, but that won=E2=80=99t last long. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m focused on the mid=
terms,=E2=80=9D one beleaguered Democratic strategist texted me yesterday. =
=E2=80=9CAnd how many Democrats we can elect in 730 days to hamper Trump fo=
r his last two years.=E2=80=9D Here are the bellwether races that the
pros are already watching=E2=80=A6<br/><br/><ul style=3D"margin:0;color:#00=
0000;font-size:16px;line-height:30px;margin-top:0;margin-bottom:0;list-styl=
e-type:square;mso-special-format:bullet"><li><i>The Spanberger signal</i>: =
Over the last decade or so, political operatives have frequently looked to =
Virginia=E2=80=94a mostly Democratic state that experiences Republican mood=
 swings every few years=E2=80=94as an early indicator of national political=
 trends. And, thanks in part to its infamous off-year election, it is <i>al=
ways</i> viewed as a referendum on the incumbent president=E2=80=99s perfor=
mance. To wit: <b>Glenn Youngkin</b>=E2=80=99s upset victory over <b>Terry<=
/b> <b>McAuliffe</b> in 2021 turned out to be a harbinger of Joe Biden=E2=
=80=99s broader challenges. <br/><br/>That=E2=80=99s why Democrats will be =
watching particularly closely when Rep. Abigail Spanberger retires at the e=
nd of this year to run for Virginia governor in 2025. She=E2=80=99s already=
 considered a strong candidate, having spent this cycle raising
piles of money for state legislature candidates. Just as important, she mad=
e sure that her successor was a Democrat. <b>Eugene Vindman</b>=E2=80=99s t=
hree-point win over the highly touted Republican candidate, retired Green B=
eret <b>Derrick Anderson</b>, was one of the few pleasant surprises for Dem=
ocrats from Tuesday night. <br/><br/>But the <i>real</i> reason Spanberger=
=E2=80=99s campaign matters for Democrats is because she=E2=80=99ll likely =
be test-piloting new messaging for the party. Back in 2020, she made waves =
among her colleagues with her vocal opposition to Democrats indulging far-l=
eft rallying cries like =E2=80=9Cdefund the police,=E2=80=9D which she dism=
issed with expletive-laden <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbW=
FpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dUQ2NTc2VqUlN6LTdkTlQ3YjV2Zz0iLCJocmVmI=
joiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud2FzaGluZ3RvbnBvc3QuY29tL3ZpZGVvL3BvbGl0aWNzL3NwYW5iZXJn=
ZXItY3JpdGljaXplcy1kZW1vY3JhdHMtc3RyYXRlZ3ktaW4tY2F1Y3VzLWNhbGwvMjAyMC8xMS8=
wNS82ZWMyYjM2OC0yNThhLTQwNjEtOTczOC1kODNlZTg5NzFjM2NfdmlkZW8uaHRtbD91dG1fY2=
FtcGFpZ249VGhlK0Jlc3QrJTI2K1RoZStCcmlnaHRlc3QrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjgxMSUyR=
jclMkYyNCUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3VzdG9tZXIuaW8iLCJpbnRlcm5hbCI6ImY2YzYw=
NjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImxpbmtfaWQiOjE5NjgwMDV9/3a421fd2417922177b47645c7a91c8=
03f181755d3ebaeed2f2cb914541aa0686" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:=
none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">exasperation</a></u>. A former C.I.A. =
and law enforcement officer, Spanberger is already being looked to as a lit=
mus test for how a more centrist flavor of Democratic politics could play i=
n a state that=E2=80=99s still blue=E2=80=94but now, just barely. </li><br/=
><li><i>Lawler=E2=80=99s big night</i>: On the Republican side, the most wa=
tched member could end up being <b>Mike Lawler</b>, who just secured a seco=
nd term in New York=E2=80=99s moderate-ish 17th District. Few in Congress h=
ad a better night than the Republican freshman incumbent, who defeated Demo=
crat <b>Mondaire Jones </b>by 25,000 votes. (Lawler=E2=80=99s margin of vic=
tory in his 2022 race against then-D.C.C.C. chairman <b>Sean Patrick Malone=
y</b> was just 1,200 votes.) Lawler=E2=80=99s margin this time was large
enough that his name is circulating as a challenger to Democratic Gov. <b>K=
athy</b> <b>Hochul</b> in 2026.<br/><br/>Lawler=E2=80=99s decision probably=
 depends on whether Hochul runs for reelection. But if he does take on Alba=
ny, it=E2=80=99ll be on very different terms than when Lee Zeldin came with=
in seven points of Hochul in 2022. Next cycle, there will be no <b>Chuck Sc=
humer</b> or <b>Kirsten Gillibrand</b> on the ballot. And Lawler may be in =
a position to uplift fellow Republicans down-ballot, too. Much like the las=
t two cycles, control for the House in 2026 may come down to the Empire Sta=
te, which Trump lost by a much smaller margin this time=E2=80=9412 points a=
gainst Harris vs. 24 points against Biden.</li></ul></td>
